", ', and

In computer systems, there are two different types of quotation marksdumb (or straight) quotes (' & ") used by machines and smart (or curly) quotes ( & ) used by humans. R uses the former only. Almost all computer keyboards only support dumb quotes, but some programs such as Microsoft Word will automatically convert dumb quotes into smart quotes. This is a great feature for writing but bad for coding because R does not recognize smart quotes:

print(Hello world)
## Error: <text>:1:7: unexpected input
## 1: print(
##           ^

If you see this error, it most likely means that your code has the wrong type of quotations marks.

As such, you are advised against using Microsoft Word or other productivity software to store R code. The best way to save R code is to type them in RStudio and save as R scripts (.R files). Use commenting # to jot notes on what the code does.

When to use print()?

Based on past experience, many students are confused about print(). It is because we intuitively think that what we see is what we get. If we see the result printed out in the console, doesnt it mean that the operation is completed in R? No.In fact, in the later part of the course when we get into more complicated operations, the values are usually not printed out in the console. Therefore, it is important that we understand when does the console give an output and when does it not.

Suppose that we want to find out the mean of a vector of numbers:

mean(1:5)
## [1] 3

After running this command, 3 is printed out in the console. But why? It is because when we run the command, the function mean() computes the result and then returns it. Since we did not assign the returned value of the function to anywhere, the value is output to the console by default. If we assign the returned value to a variable:

x <- mean(1:5)

We dont see 3 this time because the returned value of mean() is output to the variable x. If we want to know the result, we type x in the console:

x
## [1] 3

Because we did not assign the output when we run this command, the value of x is directly output to the console.

However, this default behaviour does not always apply. In fact, it only applies when the command is not inside a function. Suppose you want to design a function that outputs the input, and you would like a message to be printed out on the console when the function is running:

test <- function(y) {
  "Function running..."
  y
}
test(1)
## [1] 1

Why isnt the sentence printed out in the console? It is because inside a function, only the last line is returned. The line "Function running..." is simply disregarded. This is when print() comes in handy:

test <- function(y) {
  print("Function running...")
  y
}
test(1)
## [1] "Function running..."
## [1] 1

Wala. But note that even though you see the sentence printed out in the console, it does not mean that it is part of the returned value. The sentence is printed out because we force it to by using the function print(). The returned value of the function is still unchanged. Therefore, if we assign the output of the function to a variable, only the value 1 is stored in the variable:

x <- test(1) # assign the returned value to x
## [1] "Function running..."
x # does not include the sentence
## [1] 1

During the in-class exercise, some of you created a function similar to this:

Newspapers_set2 <- data.frame(
  name = c("NYT", "WSJ", "USATODAY", "Guardian", "AppleDaily", "MingPao"), 
  circulation = c(1.2, 3.4, 5.6, 4.7, 0.2, 0.1), 
  place = c("US", "US", "US", "UK", "HK", "HK")
)
Display_info <- function(df, text) {
  if (text %in% df$name) {
    place <- df$place[df$name == text]
    circulation <- df$circulation[df$name == text]
    print(place)
    circulation
  } else {
    "Not found. Please enter again"
  }
}
Display_info(Newspapers_set2, "WSJ")
## [1] "US"
## [1] 3.4

It is seemingly correct because you can see both the place and the circulation of the newspaper being printed out in the console, which meets the goal of the in-class exercise, isnt it? But when you assign the returned value of the function to a variable:

x <- Display_info(Newspapers_set2, "WSJ")
## [1] "US"
x
## [1] 3.4

Only the circulation is saved to x because the place is only printed not returned. That is why we need to combine the place and circulation into a single variable using paste0() as shown in the solution presented in class:

Display_info <- function(df, text) {
  if (text %in% df$name) {
    place <- df$place[df$name == text]
    circulation <- df$circulation[df$name == text]
    paste0(text, " is a newspaper in ", place, ". It has a circulation of ", circulation, " million.")
  } else {
    "Not found. Please enter again"
  }
}
x <- Display_info(Newspapers_set2, "WSJ")
x
## [1] "WSJ is a newspaper in US. It has a circulation of 3.4 million."

You may wonder, what if we want the function to return two separate values, one as the place and one as the circulation? We can return a vector:

Display_info <- function(df, text) {
  if (text %in% df$name) {
    place <- df$place[df$name == text]
    circulation <- df$circulation[df$name == text]
    c(place, circulation)
  } else {
    "Not found. Please enter again"
  }
}
x <- Display_info(Newspapers_set2, "WSJ")
x[1] # place
## [1] "US"
x[2] # circulation
## [1] "3.4"

Logical subsetting

Some of you raised question about how the x$national[x$name==text] command works. To explain it, we should first revisit how to subset a vector in R.

The most common way is by positive integers, aka the index number of the corresponding element:

newspapers <- data.frame(
  name = c("NYT", "WSJ", "USATODAY"), 
  circulation = c(1.2, 3.4, 5.6),
  national = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE)
)
newspapers$name[1] # first element
## [1] "NYT"
newspapers$circulation[2:3] # second to third element
## [1] 3.4 5.6
newspapers[1, ] # first row
##   name circulation national
## 1  NYT         1.2     TRUE
newspapers[, c(1, 3)] # first and third column
##       name national
## 1      NYT     TRUE
## 2      WSJ     TRUE
## 3 USATODAY    FALSE

Another way is by negative integers. Contrary to using positive integers, specifying negative integers exclude the corresponding element(s):

newspapers$name[-1] # exclude first element
## [1] "WSJ"      "USATODAY"
newspapers$circulation[-(2:3)] # exclude second to third element
## [1] 1.2
newspapers[-c(1, 3), ] # exclude first and third row
##   name circulation national
## 2  WSJ         3.4     TRUE
newspapers[, -1] # exclude the first column
##   circulation national
## 1         1.2     TRUE
## 2         3.4     TRUE
## 3         5.6    FALSE

The third way is by a logical vector. It selects the elements where the corresponding logical value is TRUE:

newspapers$name[c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE)] # first element
## [1] "NYT"

It returns the first element, which is "NYT", because only the first element of the logical vector is TRUE.

Similarly:

newspapers$circulation[c(FALSE, TRUE, TRUE)] # second to third element
## [1] 3.4 5.6
newspapers[c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE), ] # first row
##   name circulation national
## 1  NYT         1.2     TRUE
newspapers[, c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)] # first and third column
##       name national
## 1      NYT     TRUE
## 2      WSJ     TRUE
## 3 USATODAY    FALSE

This property is very handy because often times we only know what data we want but not where they are, rendering it impossible to subset using the index number. For example, we want to extract the circulation of New York Times:

newspapers$name == "NYT"
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE

This logical vector basically indicates that the first element of the vector is "NYT". By fitting this statement into subsetting the circulation of the newspaper:

newspapers$circulation[newspapers$name == "NYT"]
## [1] 1.2

Boom. We now have the circulation of New York Times. This technique can be applied to all logical statement, as long as they return a logical vector of the same length as the data to be subset:

newspapers$name[newspapers$circulation > 2] # select names of newspapers with circulation more than 2 million
## [1] "WSJ"      "USATODAY"
newspapers[newspapers$national != TRUE, ] # select the rows of non-national newspapers
##       name circulation national
## 3 USATODAY         5.6    FALSE

List

List can be hard to comprehend because of its flexibility and irregularity. To help visuaize and explain what a list is, allow me to borrow the explanation by Wickham (2019):

If list x is a train carrying objects, then x[[5]] is the object in car 5; x[4:6] is a train of cars 4-6. @RLangTip, https://twitter.com/RLangTip/status/268375867468681216

Lets use this metaphor to make a simple list:

x <- list(
  1:3, 
  "a", 
  4:6
)

When extracting a single element, you have two options: you can create a smaller train, i.e., fewer carriages, or you can extract the contents of a particular carriage. This is the difference between [ and [[:

From the example above, we can see that by using [ to subset a list, you still end up with a list (the train carriage) wrapping the content:

x[1]
## [[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3
class(x[1])
## [1] "list"

To extract the content from a specific element of a list, you need to use [[ instead:

x[[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3
class(x[[1]])
## [1] "integer"

If the list is named, meaning that every element have a name, we can extract the specific element by its name:

x <- list(
  first = 1:3, 
  second = "a", 
  third = 4:6
)
x[["first"]]
## [1] 1 2 3

An alternative way is to use the $ sign:

x$first
## [1] 1 2 3

The $ sign here may remind you of how you select a column from a data frame. In fact, data frame is a variant of named list in which:

  1. each element of the list represents a column;
  2. the names of the elements are the column names
  3. the length of the content in each element are identical so that a consistent row count is maintained

It is property 1) and 2) that make it possible to select a column from a data frame using $.

This is a more advanced concept so it may take some time for you to fully understand. In any case, if you want extract something from a list, it is almost certain that you would need to use [[ or $ instead of [.

Nested list: multiple $ signs

It is possible to have a list inside a list. This is called a nested list.

Consider the following nested list:

x <- list(
  first = 1:3, 
  second = list(
    nested = "a"
  ), 
  third = 4:6)

The second element of x is a list that contains "a" with the name "nested". To get to "a", you need to first select the second element of x, and then further select the first element of the list:

x[[2]][[1]]
## [1] "a"
# or
x[["second"]][["nested"]]
## [1] "a"
# or
x$second$nested
## [1] "a"

In the in-class project, the New York Times API returns the search result in the form of a nested list. If you click on the returned list object in the top right panel Environment of RStudio, you can have a glance of the structure of the list:

The returned list testing has 3 elements at its top level: status, copyright and response. While the first two are character strings, response is a list that contains another list docs and a named numeric vector meta. Therefore, if we want to extract the hit count, we need to first select the third element of testing, and then select the second element of the list, and finally select the first element of the numeric vector:

testing[[3]][[2]][1]
## hits 
## 1832
# or
testing[["response"]][["meta"]]["hits"]
## hits 
## 1832
# or
testing$response$meta["hits"]
## hits 
## 1832

When to use return()?

Some students raised a very useful questionwhen should we use return() and when should we not? To answer this, we need to first understand how does a function determines which value to return.

We have learnt that a function always returns the last line. The last line here refers to the last line of execution, not the last line in a locational sense. Consider the following function that checks whether the input value is larger than zero:

check_zero <- function(y) {
  if (y > 0) {
    "Larger than zero"
  } else if (y < 0) {
    "Less than zero"
  } else {
    "Is zero"
  }
}
check_zero(1)
## [1] "Larger than zero"
check_zero(-1)
## [1] "Less than zero"
check_zero(0)
## [1] "Is zero"

The locational last line of the function is "Is zero", but why doesnt entering 1 and -1 return "Is zero"? It is because when the input value is not 0, the line "Is zero" is never executed in the if-else clause. When you enter 1, the last line of execution is "Larger than zero". When you enter -1, the last line of execution is "Less than zero".

The use of return() in a function will break this last line rule. When the return() is executed, the function will immediate terminate and return the value wrapped inside return(). For example:

test <- function(y) {
  return(0)
  y * 2
}
test(2)
## [1] 0

This function will always return 0 because whenever the function is run, return(0) will always be executed and prematurely terminate the function before getting to the last line. The line y * 2 never get the chance of being executed.

We can rewrite our check_zero() from above by exploiting this property:

check_zero <- function(y) {
  if (y > 0) {
    return("Larger than zero")
  } 
  if (y < 0) {
    return("Less than zero")
  }
  "Is zero"
}
check_zero(1)
## [1] "Larger than zero"
check_zero(-1)
## [1] "Less than zero"
check_zero(0)
## [1] "Is zero"

This function performs exactly the same as the old one. You may wonder, why dont you just use an if-else clause? If your function involves lengthy process for some input while short process for some other input, using return() instead of if-else may make your code much easier to read:

test <- function(y) {
  if (y <= 0) {
    return(0) # always return 0 if input is less than or equal to zero
  }
  ### if input is larger than zero, 
  ### executes some hundred lines of code
}

Indeed, there is no right or wrong answer. Technically speaking, both using if-else and using return() can get you the same result. It is just a matter of programming style which is an endless topic of debate. But the ultimate goal should always be readability such that a person who is completely new to your code (e.g., your TA and the future you one week after writing the code) can easily understand what you are trying to do.

If you are still confused, the short answer is to always use return() to indicate the value that you want your function to return.

in vs.%in%

Some students mixed up in in for loop and %in%. They are two completely different concepts. The in in for loop indicates for each element in the vector, perform , while %in% is an R operator that checks whether the vector on the right contains the vector from the left. They cannot be used interchangeably.

Vectorization

In the class, we touched on the idea of vectorization and mentioned that vectorization is a key characteristic of R. But what exactly is vectorization? It essentially means the ability to perform an operation over a vector, aka a series of values. You may not be aware of the convenience of vectorization since R is the first programming language for most of you. But in fact, many other programming languages do not support vectorization by default. Suppose that you have a vector of numbers and you want to divide them all by 5. In R, you can simply run:

# Vectorized way of division by 5
numbers <- c(1.5, 2.8, 3.4, 4.7, 5.6)
numbers / 5
## [1] 0.30 0.56 0.68 0.94 1.12

But in some other programming languages, the only way to perform this operation is to use a for loop to perform the division one by one:

# Non-vectorized way of division by 5
for (i in 1:length(numbers)) {
  numbers[i] <- numbers[i] / 5
}
numbers
## [1] 0.30 0.56 0.68 0.94 1.12

Even though both ways appear to be the same, using for loop is considerably slower. The difference can be huge when you are handling a large chunk of data of up to thousands or even millions of values. The built-in support for vectorization in R is what makes it an excellent programming language for data analytics.

In the class, we introduced the function Vectorize(). It is a function to convert any existing function into a vectorized function. What does it mean? When we design our own function, oftentimes we dont think in a vectorized manner. Recall the Is_national_paper() function from the lecture slides:

Is_national_paper <- function(x, text) {
  if (text %in% x$name) {
    x$national[x$name == text]
  } else {
    "I don't know."
  }
}

This function is designed to handle one value at a time. Say, if we want to find out whether a bunch of newspapers are national or not:

text_vector <- c("NYT", "AppleDaily", "USATODAY")
Is_national_paper(newspapers, text_vector)
## Warning in if (text %in% x$name) {: the condition has length > 1 and only the
## first element will be used
## [1]  TRUE FALSE

Instead of indicating whether all three newspapers are national or not, it only returns two logical values along with a warning. It is because an if clause can only interpret one logical value at a time. But when we input a character vector into the function, text %in% x$name inside the if clause returns three logical values. In this case, the if clause only considers the first logical values and disregards the rest. Thus, "AppleDaily", which is not in the data frame, is completely ignored, and we dont get the "I don't know." output that we expect. This is clearly not what we intended to do. Long story short, the function is simply not designed to handle a vector of values as its input.

One solution is to use a for loop:

result <- c() # an empty vector
for (i in 1:length(text_vector)) {
  result[i] <- Is_national_paper(newspapers, text_vector[i])
}
result
## [1] "TRUE"          "I don't know." "FALSE"

But this is somewhat tedious. You need to create an empty vector to store the result and type extra code to construct a for loop. Worse of all, this approach can become extremely slow when handling large-scale data.

A more elegant and quicker approach is to use Vectorize():

Vector_Is_npaper <- Vectorize(Is_national_paper, "text")
Vector_Is_npaper(newspapers, text_vector)
##             NYT      AppleDaily        USATODAY 
##          "TRUE" "I don't know."         "FALSE"

By specifying the function Is_national_paper as the first argument and "text" as the second argument in Vectorize(), we are asking Vectorize() to generate a vectorized version of Is_national_paper that accepts a vector as the argument text.
